    <!-- Hardware / LED help -->
    <string name="hw_section">Hardware: ESP32-C5 Status-LEDs</string>
    <string name="hw_intro">The Waveshare ESP32-C5-WIFI6-KIT has two LEDs visible during operation.</string>
    <string name="hw_led_power_title">Power-LED (white/blue, always on)</string>
    <string name="hw_led_power_body">Lit as long as the board receives USB power. If it is off, check the USB cable and port.</string>
    <string name="hw_led_user_title">User-LED (GPIO 8, controlled by firmware)</string>
    <string name="hw_led_user_body">• Off – sniffer running normally, waiting for frames.\n• Brief flash at startup – bootloader active / app initialising.\n• Solid on – board stuck in download mode. This happens when the RTS signal asserts at connection time. The app and bridge force RTS=low after opening; if you see this with a third-party serial tool, set DTR=false, RTS=false manually.</string>
    <string name="hw_no_frames_title">No frames received although connected?</string>
    <string name="hw_no_frames_body">The sniffer starts on channel 1 (2.4 GHz). Real ITS-G5 / V2X traffic is at 5.9 GHz — RSSI −128 dBm and zero frames is normal until the channel is changed via the UART console (GPIO 11/12, not exposed on the breakout header without a probe).\n\nA test frame (payload DEADBEEF…) is sent on every boot and appears as the first entry in the frame log — this confirms USB and firmware are working.</string>
    <string name="hw_reset_title">Resetting the board from the app</string>
    <string name="hw_reset_body">The USB and BT connection screens have a "Reset on start" option that pulses RTS high for 100 ms and then low again. This soft-resets the ESP32-C5 without unplugging the cable and triggers a new test frame.</string>

